President Joseph R. Biden, Jr. and Republic of Korea (ROK) President Yoon Suk Yeol met in Cambodia to discuss their condemnation of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea's (DPRK) recent destabilizing actions, including military operations and the launch of an intercontinental ballistic missile. They also talked about joint efforts to limit the DPRK's ability to fund and advance its unlawful weapons programs. President Biden reaffirmed the U.S. commitment to the ROK's defense using a range of capabilities, including nuclear, conventional, and missile defense. They discussed providing humanitarian assistance to Ukraine and holding Russia accountable for its war against its neighbor. President Biden welcomed the ROK's new Indo-Pacific Strategy and emphasized the importance of strengthening cooperation in the region. The leaders also discussed combating the climate crisis and the role of US and ROK companies in meeting shared climate goals.